South Africa entered alert level 3 of the national lockdown today, which means many of the restrictions under alert level 4 have been eased. Wholesale and retail trade is now fully opened, alcohol is allowed to be sold at certain times, and many companies have opened their offices again. Businesses which are opening their doors have to adhere to strict guidelines to ensure the safety of their employees and clients. Every business must also have a workplace plan. To assist companies in creating a workplace plan, law firm Cliffe Dekker Hofmeyr has provided a list of 10 key aspects that must be covered in this plan. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-354287" src="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Workplace-Plan-Checklist.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="905" srcset="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Workplace-Plan-Checklist.jpg 850w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Workplace-Plan-Checklist-283x400.jpg 283w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Workplace-Plan-Checklist-304x430.jpg 304w, https://mybroadband.co.za/news/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Workplace-Plan-Checklist-768x1086.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" />